    	<h2><a name="2003-11-01" href="#2003-11-01"><font color="#660000">2003-11-01</font></a></h2>
   	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106772050477017536">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.sdtimes.com/news/088/story2.htm">SD Times: SQL 2003 to standardize XML interfaces, improve interoperability</a>.&nbsp; Here is a little on the roadmap to SQL 2003 as of October 15, 2003.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106772050477017536">11/1/2003 01:01:44 PM</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106771981863393042">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.jtc1sc32.org/">JTC1/SC32</a>.&nbsp; This is where ISO/IEC JTC1 SC32 materials are coordinated.&nbsp; It is not clear how current this material is.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106771981863393042">11/1/2003 12:50:18 PM</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106771856655233166">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://dbforums.com/arch/57/2003/7/744798">dBforums - Are DOMAINs part of SQL-99 standard?</a>.&nbsp; There is some weird business about whether DOMAINs are part of SQL yet, or is this an abuse of the concept and it is really something else, or ... what?&nbsp;[2003-11-02] Well, I figured out more of this.  DOMAIN is not part of the Core for SQL:1999, but it is there.  Whether or not it satisfies the Relational Model notion of domain is not clear.  It does appear to be close to the DISTINCT TYPE that can be created as an user datatype in SQL:1999 as well.&nbsp; It is clearly not the whole job yet, but it seems to be closer.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106771856655233166">11/1/2003 12:29:26 PM</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106771839360676739">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://sky.fit.qut.edu.au/~reye/">Jim Reye</a>.&nbsp; Jim Reye provided a seminar on What's new in SQL-99 and the PowerPoint slides can be downloaded from this page.&nbsp; I found this to be a valuable resource.&nbsp; What I find amazing is the degree to which implementations seem to pick and choose, and there is no harmony to when the extension is extended, when it is restricted, and when nothing is done about ascerting compliance in any way.&nbsp; That is what I want to find out about now [2003-11-02].<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106771839360676739">11/1/2003 12:26:33 PM</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106771793481097611">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.intelligententerprise.com/000120/scalable.shtml">Intelligent Enterprise Magazine - Scalable Systems - SQL-99's New OLAP Functions</a>.&nbsp; This article describes now nicely the OLAP functions were pulled together and appended as a supplement to the SQL:1999 statndard from ANSI.&nbsp; There are some useful links too.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106771793481097611">11/1/2003 12:18:54 PM</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106771755627377228">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.sqlx.org/">SQLX.org WebSite - Welcome!!</a>.&nbsp; This site is for the H2.3 task group on XML and SQL (formerly known as SQLX).&nbsp; Again, these pages seem to end before the January 2003 SC32 meeting in Santa Fe.&nbsp; It makes me wonder whether the whole thing has fallen apart!<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106771755627377228">11/1/2003 12:12:36 PM</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106771735849850151">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.sqlstandards.org/">ANSI & ISO Work Group's Web Site - SQL Standards</a>.&nbsp; This site is not up-to-date and it doesn't have any ANSI H2 meeting schedules beyond January 2003 in Santa Fe.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106771735849850151">11/1/2003 12:09:18 PM</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106771721545007942">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.ncits.org/tc_home/h2.htm">H2</a>.&nbsp; Well, it is apparently not ANSI anymore, but it is H2.&nbsp; How quaint.&nbsp; This is the InterNational Committee for Information Technology Standards technical committee H2 on Database.&nbsp; It was once ncits, and it still seems to be fairly US-centric.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106771721545007942">11/1/2003 12:06:55 PM</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106771699386207685">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.service-architecture.com/database/articles/sql1999.html">SQL:1999</a>.&nbsp; This is an odd but interesting article on the addition of User Defined Types to SQL.&nbsp; This is close to being able to have domains, but apparently not quite.&nbsp;There is also some sort of fragmentation around who defines SQL standards and how they lead implementation.&nbsp; A well-known problem in standards work, and a sin that I have committed too.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106771699386207685">11/1/2003 12:03:13 PM</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106771682931986603">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/tg/detail/-/0879305681/">Amazon.com: Books: SQL-99 Complete, Really</a>.&nbsp; I already have this book, and it surfaced in my search for SQL-99 information for the database class I am taking.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106771682931986603">11/1/2003 12:00:29 PM</a></span></div>
<br>
